                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/590</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Military Attaché in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">War Department</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="69" xml:id="d729fn69">Paraphrase of radiogram received at the War
                        Department, August 13, 9:54 p.m., and transmitted to the Department of
                        State.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-08-13">August 13,
                            1939</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>New military air field built by Chinese 30 miles up river. Two hundred
                    twenty-five Soviet planes recently arrived China and less than that number
                    Soviet pilots according to reliable source who states also that 60 pursuits to
                    be allotted defense of Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Barrett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
